articles.author: Idrees Ali, Phil Stewart
articles.description: U.S. Defense Secretary Lloyd Austin no longer plans to travel to South Korea, two U.S. officials told Reuters on Thursday, following South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol's botched attempt this week to impose martial law.
articles.title: Exclusive: US defense secretary scraps South Korea trip after martial law attempt

articles.author: Gabriel Stargardter
articles.description: Michel Barnier, a veteran politician who was formerly the European Union's Brexit negotiator, will be the shortest serving prime minister in modern French history.
articles.title: Barnier expected to resign as France's festering political crisis rumbles on

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: A magnitude 7 earthquake hit off the northern California coast on Thursday, prompting a tsunami warning that was later canceled for a large stretch of the California and Oregon coasts, officials said.
articles.title: Strong quake strikes off California, tsunami warning canceled

articles.author: Kylie Madry, Ted Hesson
articles.description: Mexico is seeking an agreement with U.S. President-elect Donald Trump to ensure it does not receive deportees from third countries in case of large-scale deportations of migrants from the United States, President Claudia Sheinbaum said on Thursday.
articles.title: Mexico seeks deal with Trump to avoid deported migrants from other countries

articles.author: Maxwell Adombila
articles.description: Ghana's two main presidential contenders staged rival rallies in the capital, Accra, on Thursday evening, courting voters in a final push ahead of the world's second biggest cocoa producer's legislative and presidential election set for Saturday.
articles.title: Ghana's presidential frontrunners in last-minute rally for votes

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Russian President Vladimir Putin appointed Alexander Khinshtein acting governor of southern Kursk region on Thursday, saying "crisis management" was needed in the area, which has been partly occupied by Ukrainian forces since August.
articles.title: Russia's Putin appoints new governor for partly occupied Kursk region

articles.author: Alexander Tanas
articles.description: Moldova's president on Thursday sacked Energy Minister Victor Parlicov and the prime minister called for two other senior energy officials to resign for failing to tackle an energy crisis in the small former Soviet republic.
articles.title: Moldova sacks energy minister over failure to tackle crisis

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Iraqi Foreign Minister Fuad Hussein will meet his Syrian and Iranian counterparts on Friday to discuss the situation in Syria, the Iraqi state news agency said on Thursday.
articles.title: Syrian, Iraqi, Iranian foreign ministers to meet on Friday, Iraqi state media says

articles.author: Timour Azhari, Maya Gebeily
articles.description: Hezbollah has paid out more than $50 million in cash gifts to families affected by war with Israel, its leader Naim Qassem said on Thursday, as the Iran-backed group seeks to shore up its support base after a devastating conflict with Israel.
articles.title: Hezbollah to pay total of $77 million and rent to families affected by war

articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi, Mohammed Salem
articles.description: The Israeli military killed at least 39 Palestinians in strikes across the Gaza Strip overnight, medics said on Thursday, including at least 20 in an attack that set ablaze tents sheltering displaced families in a crowded camp.
articles.title: Dozens dead in Israeli strikes on Gaza; Palestinians say Amnesty 'genocide' declaration comes too late
